#### Casualties

*   Eight American soldiers died in the botched [Operation Eagle Claw](/Operation_Eagle_Claw) on April 24–25, 1980. A grim reminder of the cost of desperation.
*   One Iranian civilian was also killed during that same disastrous operation.

*(Map of Tehran with embassy location indicated)*

This whole affair was a tangled mess of vengeance, misunderstanding, and sheer, raw political theater. America's President [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) called it "blackmail," the hostages "victims of terrorism and anarchy." The revolutionaries, on the other hand, saw it as righteous retribution for decades of American meddling, particularly their role in the 1953 coup that installed the Shah and his notoriously brutal [SAVAK](/SAVAK). The U.S. cited the [Vienna Convention](/Vienna_Convention_on_Diplomatic_Relations) and the sanctity of [diplomatic immunity](/Diplomatic_immunity), while Iran saw it as a legitimate response to perceived American hostility. A stalemate etched in stone.

The [Canadian Caper](/Canadian_Caper), a quiet operation saving six souls, was a stark contrast to the loud, public failure of [Operation Eagle Claw](/Operation_Eagle_Claw). The latter not only cost lives but also led to Secretary of State [Cyrus Vance](/Cyrus_Vance) stepping down. The [Iraqi invasion of Iran](/Iraqi_invasion_of_Iran) in September 1980 finally nudged the Iranians towards negotiation, mediated, of course, by the ever-patient [Algeria](/Algeria).

Politically, this crisis was [Carter's](/Carter%27s_presidency) albatross, a lead weight dragging him down to a landslide loss in the [1980 presidential election](/1980_United_States_presidential_election). The hostages were released, almost symbolically, just after [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) took the oath of office. In Iran, the crisis solidified [Khomeini's](/Ruhollah_Khomeini) grip and empowered the hardliners, further isolating the nation from the [Western world](/Western_world). And the U.S.? Well, they've been imposing [sanctions](/International_sanctions_against_Iran) ever since, a constant, low-grade hum of animosity over everything from [nuclear ambitions](/Nuclear_program_of_Iran) to [human rights](/Human_rights_in_the_Islamic_Republic_of_Iran).

