### Release of the Hostages

*   See also: [First inauguration of Ronald Reagan](/First_inauguration_of_Ronald_Reagan)

With the [Algiers Accords](/Algiers_Accords_(1981)) signed on January 19, 1981, the 52 American hostages were released the following day. The timing was precise: minutes after Ronald Reagan's [inaugural address](/First_inauguration_of_Ronald_Reagan). Theories abound as to why Iran waited until this exact moment, but the symbolism was undeniable.

#### Transfer to American Custody

The hostages flew from Tehran to Algiers on an [Air Algeria](/Air_Alg%C3%A9rie) [Boeing 727](/Boeing_727), where they were formally handed over to [Warren M. Christopher](/Warren_M._Christopher) as a gesture of thanks to Algeria. The flight continued to [Rhein-Main Air Base](/Rhein-Main_Air_Base) in West Germany, then to a U.S. Air Force hospital in [Wiesbaden](/Wiesbaden). There, former President Carter met them. After medical checks and debriefings, they flew to [Shannon, Ireland](/Shannon,_County_Clare), greeted by a large crowd, and finally to [Stewart Air National Guard Base](/Stewart_Air_National_Guard_Base) in [Newburgh, New York](/Newburgh_(town),_New_York). A bus journey took them to West Point, where they stayed at the [Thayer Hotel](/Thayer_Hotel) for three days, receiving a hero's welcome. Ten days later, a [ticker tape parade](/Ticker_tape_parade) through Manhattan's [Canyon of Heroes](/Canyon_of_Heroes) celebrated their return.

